00:55.181 --> 00:57.264
And that, of course, from the real and from the fake.

00:57.885 --> 01:03.733
And the discriminators simply try to discriminate only in these windows, whether it's real or fake.

01:04.154 --> 01:13.828
And now we're a bit more into the GAN setting, where you simply have one data point of the real and one data point of the fake, and you have to compare them.

01:13.808 --> 01:32.982
And this here, I believe, is one of the keys why this model generalizes, because the discriminators basically they try to assess whether a short sequence sounds like real or sounds like fake, and whether the two samples sound alike in different scales of time.

01:32.962 --> 01:38.530
And by only doing this on these short scales, the loss sort of generalizes.

01:38.651 --> 01:48.025
Otherwise, if you compare it on the entire sound wave, it would just reduce to comparing point by point right here.

01:48.546 --> 01:56.117
And if the generator produces something that's not exactly aligned, then of course every point would be wrong.

01:56.097 --> 01:58.100
You run into all sorts of questions.

01:58.180 --> 02:10.296
So this is a set of five discriminators that all try to take each takes a different length of subsound of this wave tries to discriminate real from fake.

02:10.316 --> 02:11.538
